markdown# Verbjective — Windsurf Rules

## Project Overview
Verbjective is a professional, academic online English tutoring platform. There is one tutor and multiple students. Students book 1-on-1 live sessions via Zoom or Google Meet. The platform supports pay-per-session and subscription payment models. Invoices are generated as PDFs. The platform is multilingual from day one.

## Tech Stack
- Next.js 14, App Router, TypeScript (strict mode)
- Tailwind CSS
- Supabase (Postgres, Auth, Storage, RLS)
- Resend + React Email for transactional emails
- react-pdf/renderer for invoice PDFs
- next-intl for internationalisation
- React Hook Form + Zod for all forms
- Vercel for deployment

## Code Rules
- TypeScript strict mode always — no `any` types ever
- Server components by default — only use `use client` when interactivity requires it
- All forms use React Hook Form with Zod validation
- All Supabase queries must use typed clients generated from the schema
- All dates stored in UTC, displayed in user's local timezone
- All monetary values stored as integers in ZAR cents to avoid floating point errors
- Sanitise all user inputs
- Never hardcode secrets — all sensitive values come from environment variables
- Never write to or read from `.env.local` — the developer manages that file manually

## Folder Structure
- `/app/(public)` — public pages (landing, contact, sign-in, sign-up)
- `/app/(protected)/dashboard/student` — student dashboard
- `/app/(protected)/dashboard/tutor` — tutor dashboard (role-gated)
- `/components/ui` — reusable UI primitives
- `/components/tutor` — tutor-specific components
- `/components/student` — student-specific components
- `/components/emails` — React Email templates
- `/components/pdf` — React PDF invoice template
- `/lib/supabase` — server and client Supabase helpers
- `/lib/resend.ts` — email utility
- `/lib/pricing.ts` — pricing calculation logic
- `/lib/invoice.ts` — invoice generation logic
- `/messages` — next-intl translation files
- `/supabase/migrations` — all SQL migrations
- `/types/index.ts` — all shared TypeScript types and enums

## Security Rules
- All dashboard routes are protected by Next.js middleware
- `/dashboard/tutor` is role-gated — only users with role `tutor` may access it
- Students may only read and write their own data (enforced by RLS)
- The tutor may read all student data (enforced by RLS)
- POPIA and GDPR compliance must be maintained — consent is stored per user

## Database Rules
- Never bypass RLS
- Never use the service role key on the client side
- The service role key is only used in server-side API routes and server actions
- All new tables must have RLS enabled and appropriate policies
- Run new migrations as SQL files in `/supabase/migrations` — never alter tables manually

## Design Rules
- Visual style: professional and academic
- Tailwind only — no inline styles, no CSS modules
- Mobile responsive on every page and component
- Loading skeletons on all data-fetching components
- Error boundaries on all dashboard pages
- All public-facing copy must pass through next-intl translation keys — never hardcode display strings

## Business Logic
- Session price = determined by level (beginner/intermediate/advanced) × duration (30/60/90 min) from `pricing_config` table
- Subscribers get a configurable discount rate stored in `app_settings` 
- Subscription session limits are stored in `app_settings` and configurable by the tutor
- Cancellations must be at least 24 hours before the session start time
- When a pay-per-session booking is confirmed, generate a PDF invoice automatically
- Both tutor and student may submit one optional post-session feedback message per booking
- The tutor assigns English levels to students — students cannot set their own level

## Communication Rules
- No in-app messaging system
- Post-session feedback is the only direct communication channel on the platform
- The public contact form writes to `contact_submissions` — this is for pre-signup enquiries only
- Session reminders are sent via email 24 hours before a session

## When in Doubt
- Ask before assuming
- Never delete or modify existing migration files — create new ones
- Never change the folder structure without being instructed to
- Always confirm what you have built before moving to the next task
